snippet.textDisplay:
So the F body trans am ram air is also not a real ram air? I’m pretty sure the mid to late 60s GM ram air was real so they put it on the F body to “celebrate” the classic models.

I’m currently looking for a 98 and up trans am,preferably the WS6 package. Automatic is ok but 6speed is preferred. Any color okay except for black,if you have black then I would want room to negotiate some money off so I can wrap it/repaint it. Email me Deanwheelz@gmail.com

I used to love the F body’s and still do... I was a kid/teenager when these were out and in 2000 I got my first car. I wanted an F body but the V8s were out my price range so I found a 91 Ford Thunderbird with the optional 302 5.0HO for $900,I couldn’t pass that up. Few months later my friend got a 94-95 trans am LT1 and that thing was bad ass but I remember it drove like shit,it was awful over unsmooth pavement and every time it hit a pothole the car felt like it was going to fall apart,also it rattled and vibrated all my organs. I still loved it though cause I know its not a Lexus but still I remember test driving a 99 Mustang GT convertible when I was looking to upgrade to my second car and it felt a little better over bad pavement and pot holes,I’m sure the hard top would of been even better and the one I test drove was a salvage title too. Ultimately I found a 94 Ford Probe GT for a good price,I drove it for a little and flipped it for a low mile great condition 96 Thunderbird with 4.6 V8 and sold it for a huge profit. I was a little older by now and became a huge BMW enthusiast so I wanted one badly but I got a great deal on a Acura legend that I flipped little later for my first of many BMWs that I had since. It was a mint 92 e36 325i sport which I sold for a 96 328i then sold for 97 540i and then I wanted the sport package so i sold it for a 99 540i sport package... list goes on and on.
I also had a 94 Lincoln LSC for a few weeks before I got my first 3 series.

snippet.textDisplay: I had a 98 ws6 with very low miles.   They do indeed have some flaws but overal I loved the car. For me the main flaws were the body started getting rust dots on the underbody and small rust spots under the hood even though it was a very low k car. They didn't seem to protect them as good as they should have. My T56 was a pig to shift especially when needed and that's a problem for a go fast car. The made in Mexico speakers blew early on mine I must have had it up too loud. Lots of little rattles but I don't think I have owned any car that didn't have some kind of noise. Fuel pump access is a bastard on these cars. On the ws6 the door panels can snap at the top but mine was ok so it must be from people slamming the doors. The engine bay is super tight. Getting to the clutch bleeder valve is super hard some people cut through the body to get to it just like the fuel pump.

snippet.textDisplay: I have a modded 98 Z28 with 51,000 miles. I don't race it as much as I used to. I mostly just bring it to car shows these days. But I've beaten some newer muscle cars on the road with it. When I say newer, I mean mostly cars that were manufactured in the first decade of the 2000's. And I've only added long tube headers, a large intake manifold, ported cylinder heads, 4:10 gears, and a loudmouth SLP exhaust. The thing is, these 4th gen Camaros weigh a lot less than the newer muscle cars, which helps things. New muscles cars are way too heavy for their own good.
